IRL}}|| Taipei Representative Office in Ireland || [[Harry Tseng]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/IE]\n|-\n|{{ISR}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Tel Aviv || [[Chi Yun-sheng]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201402090002.aspx |title=Taiwan's new representative to Israel to assume duties this week &#124; Politics &#124; FOCUS TAIWAN - CNA ENGLISH NEWS |publisher=Focustaiwan.tw |date= |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref> || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/IL]\n|-\n|{{ITA}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in Italy|Ufficio di Rappresentanza di Taipei in Italia]] || [[Stanley Kao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/IT]\n|-\n|{{JPN}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in Japan]] || [[Frank Hsieh]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/JP]\n|-\n|{{JOR}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Jordan || [[Chang Yun-ping]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/JO]\n|-\n|{{KWT}}|| Taipei Commercial Representative Office in the State of Kuwait || [[Liu Kuo-hsing]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/KW]\n|-\n|{{LVA}}|| Taipei Mission in the Republic of Latvia || [[Andy Chin]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/LV]\n|-\n|{{MAC}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Macau]] || [[Lu Chang-shui]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://macaubusinessdaily.com/Politics/Taiwan%E2%80%99s-man-Macau-has-creative-approach |title=Taiwan\u2019s man in Macau has creative approach |publisher=Macau Business Daily |accessdate=2014-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019142951/http://macaubusinessdaily.com/Politics/Taiwan%E2%80%99s-man-Macau-has-creative-approach |archivedate=2013-10-19 }}</ref> || [http://www.boca.gov.tw/ct.asp?xItem=%201373&ctNode=801&mp=2]\n|-\n|{{MYS}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Malaysia]] || [[Lo Yu-chung]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/MY]\n|-\n|{{MEX}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Mexico|Oficina Econ\u00f3mica y Cultural de Taipei en M\u00e9xico]] || [[Carlos Liao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/MX]\n|-\n|{{MGL}}|| [[Taipei Trade and Economic Representative Office in Ulaanbaatar]] || [[Yang Syin-yi]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/MN]\n|-\n|{{MMR}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Myanmar || Zhang Jun<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roc-taiwan.org/mm/post/957.html|title=\u99d0\u7dec\u7538\u4ee3\u8868\u8a2a\u554f\u7dec\u5317\u50d1\u793e\u53ca\u50d1\u6821|website=\u99d0\u7dec\u7538\u53f0\u5317\u7d93\u6fdf\u6587\u5316\u8fa6\u4e8b\u8655 (Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Myanmar)|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/mm/index.html]\n|-\n|{{NLD}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in the Netherlands]] || [[James Lee (diplomat)|James Lee]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/NL]\n|-\n|{{NZL}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in New Zealand]] || [[Charng Yii-Lih]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/NZ]\n|-\n|{{NGA}}|| [[Taipei Trade Office in the Federal Republic of Nigeria]] || [[Morgan Chao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/NG]\n|-\n|{{OMA}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office, Muscat, Oman || [[Liao Kang-min]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/OM]\n|-\n|{{PNG}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Papua New Guinea || [[Hu Chun-pu]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/PG]\n|-\n|{{PER}}|| Oficina Econ\u00f3mica y Cultural de Taipei, Lima, Rep\u00fablica del Per\u00fa || [[Alejandro Huang]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/PE]\n|-\n|{{PHL}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in the Philippines]] || [[Lin Song-huann]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/PH]\n|-\n|{{POL}}|| Biuro Przedstawicielskie Tajpej w Polsce || [[Chen Ming-cheng]]<ref name=\"Poland India\">[http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201507080031.aspx Two diplomats sworn in before departing for Poland, India], ''[[Focus Taiwan]]'', July 8, 2015</ref> || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/PL]\n|-\n|{{PRT}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Centre, Lisbon, Portugal|Centro Econ\u00f3mico e Cultural de Taipei]] || [[Her Jian-gueng]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/PT]\n|-\n|{{RUS}}|| Representative Office in Moscow for the Taipei-Moscow Economic and Cultural Coordination Commission || [[Chen Chun-shen]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/RU]\n|-\n|{{SAU}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] || [[Lin Jinn-jong]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SA]\n|-\n|{{SIN}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in Singapore]] || [[Francis Liang]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SG]\n|-\n|{{SVK}}|| Taipei Representative Office, Bratislava || Andrew Chang || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/sk]\n|-\n|{{ZAF}}|| [[Taipei Liaison Office in the Republic of South Africa]] || [[Matthew Chou]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/ZA]\n|-\n|{{KOR}}|| [[Taipei Mission in Korea]] || Daniel Diann-wen Tang || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/KR]\n|-\n|{{ESP}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Spain|Oficina Econ\u00f3mica y Cultural de Taipei]] || [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Liu]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/ES]\n|-\n|{{SWE}}|| [[Taipei Mission in Sweden]] || [[Daniel Liao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SE]\n|-\n|{{SUI}}|| Taipei Cultural and Economic Delegation in Switzerland || [[Liu Bang-zyh]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/CH]\n|-\n|{{THA}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Thailand]] || [[Tung Chen-yuan]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/TH]\n|-\n|{{TUR}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Mission in Ankara]] || James Chen || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/TR]\n|-\n|{{UAE}}|| The Commercial Office of Taipei || [[Chang Wang-lu]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/DXB]\n|-\n|{{GBR}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in the U.K.]] || [[David Y. L. Lin|David Lin]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/UK]\n|-\n|{{USA}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States]] || [[Stanley Kao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/US]\n|-\n|{{VNM}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Vietnam]] || [[Richard R. C. Shih]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/VN]\n|}\n\n== Former representative offices ==\n*{{flag|Bangladesh}} - Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Bangladesh (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Center in India]] and [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Thailand]])\n*{{flag|Bolivia}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[La Paz]] (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Argentina]])\n*{{flag|Guam}} (suspended in 2017, transferred to Embassy of the Republic of China in [[Palau]])\n*{{flag|Libya}} - [[Taiwan Commercial Office in Tripoli]] (closed in 2011, transferred to Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Jordan)\n*{{flag|Norway}} - [[Taipei Representative Office in Norway]] (closed in 2017, transferred to [[Taipei Mission in Sweden]])\n*{{flag|Uruguay}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[Montevideo]] (closed, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Argentina]])\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[Caracas]] (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Commercial Office in Bogot\u00e1, Colombia]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[Foreign relations of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n* [[Chinese Taipei]]\n* [[Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office]]\n* [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Canada]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of Taiwan]]\n* [[Timeline of diplomatic relations of the Republic of China]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080424074047/http://www.taiwanembassy.org/mp.asp?mp=1 Overseas Office Republic of China (Taiwan)]\n*[http://www.boca.gov.tw/mp?mp=2 Bureau of Consular Affairs, Republic of China (Taiwan)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080622005317/http://www.cieca.org.tw/DB/english_web/index.asp Chinese International Economic Association Cooperation]\n\n{{Diplomatic missions of the Republic of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Taipei Economic and Cultural Offices]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taipei_Economic_and_Cultural_Representative_Office"}
{"title_page": "Rastoder", "text_new": "{{no references|date=November 2013}}\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n'''Rastoder''' or '''Hrastoder''' is a Slavic surname. The bearers are predominantly [[Bosniaks of Montenegro]] and [[Muslims by nationality]] originating from [[Bihor (region)|Bihor]], a region in northern Montenegro ([[Sand\u017eak]]), which encompasses parts of the municipalities of [[Berane]] and [[Bijelo Polje]]. \n\n==History==\nAccording to a legend, the ancestors of the Rastoder family were from [[Ku\u010di]]. These ancestors emigrated from Ku\u010di either in the 17th or 18th century. One part of the family went to [[Dupilo]] in [[Crmnica]], and the other to the mountains of [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]], of which the Medunjani descend from. The family in Dupilo, because of a blood revenge (krvna osveta, or [[Gjakmarrja|gjakmarrje]]), emigrated north, but a part of the family (known as the [[Petrovi\u0107]] at that time) decided to stay. The descendants of these Petrovi\u0107s claim that the [[Metropolitan of Cetinje]] told them that they couldn't be known as Petrovi\u0107 any longer, so they instead adopted the name '''Hrstoderi''' (later '''Hrastoderi''') because they avenged and hung a man on an oak tree (''hrast''), hence their surname.\n\nAnother saying, not too different from the previous one, says that the ancestors of the Rastoders emigrated to Radmanci and converted to [[Islam]]. They didn't have enough food when they arrived in Radmanci, so they peeled off the bark of oak trees (''hrastovi'') in order to enlarge the amount of flour for bread. It is not excluded that by that only oak valley came the surname ''Hrastoder''.\n\nA third story, more of a legend, says that before the coming of the Turks, there lived some ''Rasodijeri'', however, it is not certain whether if they were [[Bogomils]] or others, maybe even [[paganism|Pagans]], but later converted to Islam. They were recorded in books in mosques as ''Hrastoderi'' rather than ''Rasodijeri''.\n\nThe surname without the H (Rastoder) was realised during and after the period of the [[Kingdom of Montenegro]], in the registers, instead of being located in mosques, were located in local town and the Hrastoderi were recorded as Rastoderi as the registrars were Montenegrins and even today, the phoneme ''H'' isn't pronounced by Montenegrins and wasn't either at that time.\n\nSome descendants of Rastoder families of Bihor have changed their surnames, such as the [[Kr\u0161i\u0107]] and [[Nurkovi\u0107]] in [[Ro\u017eaje]], as well as [[Medunjanin]].{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n\n==People==\n*[[Rifat Rastoder]], Montenegrin Bosniak politician and deputy speaker of the [[Parliament of Montenegro]]\n*[[\u0160erbo Rastoder]], Montenegrin Bosniak historian and activist for Bosniak rights in Montenegro.\n*[[Osman Rastoder]], (1882\u20131946) Montenegrin Bosniak religious leader and pro-Nazi collaborator. He commanded the [[Sand\u017eak Muslim militia|Muslim militia]] in upper Bihor during the World War II occupation of Sand\u017eak.\n\n{{surname}}\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin-language surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{no references|date=November 2013}}\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n'''Rastoder''' or '''Hrastoder''' is a Slavic surname. The bearers are predominantly [[Bosniaks of Montenegro]] and [[Muslims by nationality]] originating from [[Bihor (region)|Bihor]], a region in northern Montenegro ([[Sand\u017eak]]), which encompasses parts of the municipalities of [[Berane]] and [[Bijelo Polje]]. \n\n==History==\nAccording to a legend, the ancestors of the Rastoder family were from [[Ku\u010di]]. These ancestors emigrated from Ku\u010di either in the 17th or 18th century. One part of the family went to [[Dupilo]] in [[Crmnica]], and the other to the mountains of [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]], of which the Medunjani descend from. The family in Dupilo, because of a blood revenge (krvna osveta), emigrated north, but a part of the family (known as the [[Petrovi\u0107]] at that time) decided to stay. The descendants of these Petrovi\u0107s claim that the [[Metropolitan of Cetinje]] told them that they couldn't be known as Petrovi\u0107 any longer, so they instead adopted the name '''Hrstoderi''' (later '''Hrastoderi''') because they avenged and hung a man on an oak tree (''hrast''), hence their surname.\n\nAnother saying, not too different from the previous one, says that the ancestors of the Rastoders emigrated to Radmanci and converted to [[Islam]]. They didn't have enough food when they arrived in Radmanci, so they peeled off the bark of oak trees (''hrastovi'') in order to enlarge the amount of flour for bread. It is not excluded that by that only oak valley came the surname ''Hrastoder''.\n\nA third story, more of a legend, says that before the coming of the Turks, there lived some ''Rasodijeri'', however, it is not certain whether if they were [[Bogomils]] or others, maybe even [[paganism|Pagans]], but later converted to Islam. They were recorded in books in mosques as ''Hrastoderi'' rather than ''Rasodijeri''.\n\nThe surname without the H (Rastoder) was realised during and after the period of the [[Kingdom of Montenegro]], in the registers, instead of being located in mosques, were located in local town and the Hrastoderi were recorded as Rastoderi as the registrars were Montenegrins and even today, the phoneme ''H'' isn't pronounced by Montenegrins and wasn't either at that time.\n\nSome descendants of Rastoder families of Bihor have changed their surnames, such as the [[Kr\u0161i\u0107]] and [[Nurkovi\u0107]] in [[Ro\u017eaje]], as well as [[Medunjanin]].{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n\n==People==\n*[[Rifat Rastoder]], Montenegrin Bosniak politician and deputy speaker of the [[Parliament of Montenegro]]\n*[[\u0160erbo Rastoder]], Montenegrin Bosniak historian and activist for Bosniak rights in Montenegro.\n*[[Osman Rastoder]], (1882\u20131946) Montenegrin Bosniak religious leader and pro-Nazi collaborator. He commanded the [[Sand\u017eak Muslim militia|Muslim militia]] in upper Bihor during the World War II occupation of Sand\u017eak.\n\n{{surname}}\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin-language surnames]]\n", "name_user": "Balkanite", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rastoder"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 East Carolina Pirates men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=2019\u201320\n  |prev_year=2018\u201319\n  |next_year=2020\u201321\n  |team=East Carolina Pirates\n  |image=East Carolina Pirates wordmark.svg\n  |image_size=150\n  |conference=American Athletic Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=AAC\n  |record= 11\u201320\n  |conf_record= 5\u201313\n  |head_coach= [[Joe Dooley (basketball)|Joe Dooley]]\n  |hc_year = 2nd, 6th overall\n  |asst_coach1= [[Steve Roccaforte]]\n  |asst_coach2= Raphael Chillious\n  |asst_coach3= George Wright-Easy\n  |stadium=[[Williams Arena at Minges Coliseum|Williams Arena]] (8,000)\n  |champion=\n  |bowl=\n  |bowl_result=\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 American Athletic Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2019\u201320 East Carolina Pirates men's basketball team''' represents [[East Carolina University]] during the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The Pirates are led by second year head coach, [[Joe Dooley (basketball)|Joe Dooley]], who previously coached the Pirates from 1995\u20131999, and play their home games at [[Williams Arena at Minges Coliseum]] as sixth-year members of the [[American Athletic Conference]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.witn.com/content/sports/AAC-announces-ECUs-home-and-road-basketball-opponents-511526682.html|title=AAC announces ECU's home and road basketball opponents|last=Athletics|first=E. C. U.|website=www.witn.com|language=english|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Previous season==\nThe [[2018\u201319 East Carolina Pirates men's basketball team|Pirates]] finished the [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319 season]] 10\u201321, 3\u201315 in [[2018\u201319 American Athletic Conference men's basketball season|AAC play]] to finish in 11th place. They lost in the first round of the [[2019 American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|AAC Tournament]] to [[2018\u201319 Wichita State Shockers men's basketball team|Wichita State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansas.com/sports/college/wichita-state/article227834219.html|title=Wichita State moving on in the AAC tournament after cruising to win over East Carolina|last=Eldridge|first=Taylor|date=|website=The Wichita Eagle|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Offseason==\n===Departures===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Reason for departure\n|-\n| Isaac Fleming || 0 || G || 6'3\" || 195 || {{sort|4.5|RS Senior}} || [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington, DE]] || Graduated\n|-\n| K. J. Davis || 2 || G || 6'5\" || 200 || {{sort|2|Sophomore}} || [[Portsmouth, Virginia|Portsmout, VA]] || Transferred to [[Samford Bulldogs men's basketball|Samford]]\n|-\n| Tyler Foster || 5 || G || 6'5\" || 190 || {{sort|1|Freshman}} || [[Baltimore|Baltimore, MD]] || Transferred to [[Youngstown State Penguins men's basketball|Youngstown State]]\n|-\n| Tae Hardy || 10 || G || 6'2\" || 190 || {{sort|1|Freshman}} || [[Ellenwood, Georgia|Ellenwood, GA]] || Transferred to [[Pearl River Community College|Pearl River CC]]\n|-\n| Justin Whatley || 13 || F || 6'8\" || 240 || {{sort|2|Sophomore}} || [[Chesapeake, Virginia|Chesapeake, VA]] || Transferred to [[North Carolina Central Eagles men's basketball|North Carolina Central]]\n|-\n| Deshaun Wade || 22 || G || 6'2\" || 200 || {{sort|1|Freshman}} ||| [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach, VA]] || Transferred to [[Longwood Lancers men's basketball|Longwood]]\n|-\n| Rico Quinton || 23 || F/C || 6'9\" || 240 || {{sort|1|Freshman}} || [[Newbern, Tennessee|Newbern, TN]] || Left the team due to personal reasons\n|-\n| John Whitley || 24 || G || 6'0\" || 170 || {{sort|3|Junior}} || [[Washington, D.C.]] || Walk-on; left the team due to personal reaso